==English==

===Etymology===
From {{compound|snow|storm|lang=en}}. Compare Saterland Frisian {{m|stq|Sneestoarm||snowstorm}}, West Frisian {{m|fy|sniestoarm||snowstorm}}, German {{m|de|Schneesturm||snowstorm}}, Dutch {{m|nl|sneeuwstorm||snowstorm}}, Swedish {{m|sv|snöstorm||snowstorm}}, Icelandic {{m|is|snjóstormur||snowstorm}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈsnəʊstɔːm/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-snowstorm.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Bad [[weather]] involving blowing [[wind]]s and [[snow]], or blowing winds and heavy [[snowfall]] amount.
# A [[snow globe]].
#* '''1947''', {{w|Dornford Yates}}, ''The Berry Scene'', Ward, Lock & Co., {{gbooks|wWYIAQAAIAAJ|273|snowstorm}}:
#*: As we made our way down, my eye was caught by a '''snowstorm'''—one of those little glass balls, with a baby cottage inside.

